          "body": "Ezekiel 40 does not contain the return of God's glory — that comes in 43:1-5, when the glory of the LORD enters the temple by the east gate. What chapter 40 does is prepare a house worthy of that return. The exiles had watched the glory depart from a defiled, measured-as-unworthy temple (chs. 8-11). Now God measures a new temple — and measures it His way, with His cubit, through His angelic agent, on a mountain no human hand raised. The movement from chapter 40's blueprint to chapter 43's glory-return is the architectural expression of the promise that runs through chapters 34-37: God will gather His people, give them a new heart, and dwell among them again (37:27: 'My dwelling place also will be with them'). Chapter 40 is the dwelling place. The argument of the chapter is ultimately not about cubits — it is about the character of a God who, after twenty-five years of exile, does not say 'start over however you can.' He says: 'Here is exactly what I want. Measure it. Declare it. I am coming back.'"
